        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "I went with CursorHold because that's pretty much exactly what's needed.\r\nLike my issue in the first place was that the diagnostic presentation is changed on every cursor move and it causes flicker. To resolve this need to change presentation only when stop moving the cursor around - `CursorHold` event does exactly that. And to revert that, the presentation needs to be changed only when cursor changes line - CurosrMoved event.\r\n\r\nSo even though I myself called it \"debounce\", it's not just debouncing, it's asymmetric in terms of delays between stop and move.\r\n\r\nIf we go with timers, it sure can provide similar behavior, but I think that would be another CursorHold and we already have one.\r\n\r\nRegarding the `updatetime` - I agree that's an issue. But I think the problem is that CursorHold is controlled with `updatetime` that initially controlled the write of swapfiles - completely unrelated. I believe I remember seeing someone suggesting adding a separate option for CursorHold (though I might be imagining things.) Maybe it's another reason to consider it? Outside the scope of this PR, but maybe for 0.13?\r\n\r\nI will go with whatever implementation we settle on, just wanted to say me piece.\r\n\r\nP.S.\r\nI noticed that I didn't handle movement within a line properly, will push a fix now. Also will update the doc to mention `updatetime` as a part of current implementation.\r\nWill rework if we end up going with timers.",
