        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> Regarding the `updatetime` - I agree that's an issue. But I think the problem is that CursorHold is controlled with `updatetime` that initially controlled the write of swapfiles - completely unrelated.\r\n\r\nThat's a rather big (blocking) problem for the immediate purposes of this PR, since many users will be disoriented if this LSP feature takes 4 seconds to update. \r\n\r\nWhy not use a timer instead? \r\n\r\n> I remember seeing someone suggesting adding a separate option for CursorHold\r\n\r\nI've suggested that, and it's tentatively in scope, but also not very urgent since we have `vim.defer_fn`, `vim.fn.timer_start`, etc?\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n> I went with CursorHold because that's pretty much exactly what's needed.\r\n\r\nIf it were an elegant approach then it might be worth doing, but the code here is not \"trivial\" so I am wondering what it gains vs a timer. And thus also still wondering why we can have a generic (private) debounce util.",
            "created_at": "2026-05-14T16:20:26Z",
            "html_url": "https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/39542#issuecomment-4452514528",
            "id": 4452514528,
            "issue_url": "https://api.github.com/repos/neovim/neovim/issues/39542",
            "node_id": "IC_kwDOAPphoM8AAAABCWP64A",
            "performed_via_github_app": null,
            "reactions": {
                "+1": 0,
                "-1": 0,
                "confused": 0,
                "eyes": 0,
                "heart": 0,
                "hooray": 0,
                "laugh": 0,
                "rocket": 0,
                "total_count": 0,
                "url": "https://api.github.com/repos/neovim/neovim/issues/comments/4452514528/reactions"
            },
            "updated_at": "2026-05-14T16:20:26Z",
            "url": "https://api.github.com/repos/neovim/neovim/issues/comments/4452514528",
            "user": {
                "avatar_url": "https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/1359421?v=4",
                "events_url": "https://api.github.com/users/justinmk/events{/privacy}",
                "followers_url": "https://api.github.com/users/justinmk/followers",
                "following_url": "https://api.github.com/users/justinmk/following{/other_user}",
                "gists_url": "https://api.github.com/users/justinmk/gists{/gist_id}",
                "gravatar_id": "",
                "html_url": "https://github.com/justinmk",
                "id": 1359421,
                "login": "justinmk",
                "node_id": "MDQ6VXNlcjEzNTk0MjE=",
                "organizations_url": "https://api.github.com/users/justinmk/orgs",
                "received_events_url": "https://api.github.com/users/justinmk/received_events",
                "repos_url": "https://api.github.com/users/justinmk/repos",
                "site_admin": false,
                "starred_url": "https://api.github.com/users/justinmk/starred{/owner}{/repo}",
                "subscriptions_url": "https://api.github.com/users/justinmk/subscriptions",
                "type": "User",
                "url": "https://api.github.com/users/justinmk",
                "user_view_type": "public"
            }
        },
        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "OK, let's dial back a little and sorry for it being a long one, but I want everything to be clear.\r\nThe issue I'm trying to solve is that immediate changes to the display of current line diagnostic causes flicker when moving around.\r\n\r\nThe desired behavior:\r\n1. when moving around - presentation doesn't change\r\n2. when movement stops - after a timeout redraw diagnostics, expanding `current_line` state\r\n3. when moving __to a different line__ - collapse `current_line` state immediately\r\n\r\nThis asymmetry between delayed entering and immediate leaving of the \"hold\" state is important because I'm trying to prevent flicker.\r\nAnd if movement off the line would be updated with a delay as well, it would cause another text movement while a user moves the cursor.\r\n\r\nNow it works as:\r\n- on CursorHold `current_line` presentation is expanded (unless already expanded) and CursorMoved autocmd is added\r\n- CursorMoved checks whether cursor line has changed, no - no-op, yes - immediately collapse current line state and remove CursorMoved autocmd\r\n\r\nTo achieve same behavior with timers we'd still need to track the hold_line state to change it with or without delay.\r\nIt will also require using only CursorMoved which is more much more frequent. Most of the time it will just reset the timer which won't kill performance, but still something to keep in mind.\r\nIt will add another option to `vim.diagnostic.Opts`, like `current_line_trigger_delay` with the default value of ~500ms.\r\n\r\nA straightforward debounce function could be the following:\r\n```lua\r\n---@generic T: function\r\n---@param fn T\r\n---@param delay integer\r\n---@return T\r\nfunction M.debounce(fn, delay)\r\n  local timer = assert(vim.uv.new_timer())\r\n\r\n  return function(...)\r\n    if timer:is_active() then\r\n      timer:stop()\r\n    end\r\n    local args = { ... }\r\n    timer:start(delay, 0, function()\r\n      timer:stop()\r\n      vim.schedule(function()\r\n        fn(unpack(args))\r\n      end)\r\n    end)\r\n  end\r\nend\r\n```\r\n\r\nAnd with that function implementation would become this:\r\n```lua\r\nlocal function within_line_hold(buf, augroup, delay, on_hold, on_move)\r\n  local hold_line = -1\r\n  local delayed_hold = vim.lsp.util.debounce(function()\r\n    local line = api.nvim_win_get_cursor(0)[1]\r\n    if line == hold_line then\r\n      return\r\n    end\r\n\r\n    hold_line = line\r\n    on_hold()\r\n  end, delay)\r\n\r\n  api.nvim_create_autocmd('CursorMoved', {\r\n    buf = buf,\r\n    group = augroup,\r\n    callback = function()\r\n      local current_line = api.nvim_win_get_cursor(0)[1]\r\n      if hold_line ~= -1 and current_line ~= hold_line then\r\n        on_move()\r\n        hold_line = -1\r\n      end\r\n\r\n      delayed_hold()\r\n    end,\r\n  })\r\nend\r\n```\r\n\r\nIt avoids the complexity of 2 events, but it doesn't remove the complexity of managing `current_line` state, delay asymmetry, and extra fired CursorMoved events. Also since the timer is not exposed, the only option is to rely on Lua GC to clean it up. I wouldn't call it much simpler overall, though it's subjective. ¯\\_(ツ)_/¯\r\n\r\nAs much as I like the approach of surgically triggering only the necessary events, I get that it will fall on maintainers to ... maintain ... it.\r\nSo if you like the debounce approach better or have other suggestions, just say a word.\r\nThanks!",
